iques -- t21. Piecing, Attachments, Repairs -- t22. Polychromy in Greek Sculpture -- tPart VIII: Afterlife -- t23. The Legacy of Greek Sculpture -- tContributors -- tIndex of Museums -- tIndex of Artists0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Handbook of Greek Sculpture aims to provide a detailed examination of current research and directions in the field. Bringing together an international cast of contributors from Greece, Italy, France, Great Britain, Germany, and the United States, the volume incorporates new areas of research, such as the sculptures of Messene and Macedonia, sculpture in Roman Greece, and the contribution of Greek sculptors in Rome, as well as important aspects of Greek sculpture like techniques and patronage. The written sources (literary and epigraphical) are explored in dedicated chapters, as are function and iconography and the reception of Greek sculpture in modern Europe. Inspired by recent exhibitions on Lysippos and Praxiteles, the book also revisits the style and the personal contributions of the great masters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSculpturezGreecexHistory. 0aSculpture, Greek. 4aAncient Greek history. 4aAntike. 4aArt history. 4aEinfluss. 4aGreek sculpture. 4aGriechische Plastik. 4aRom. 7aART / History / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAncient Greek history.  aart history.  asculpture.1 aAdornato, Gianfranco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamaskos, Dimitris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDillon, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacob, Raphaël, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.